    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Teachers' Merit Pay</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Mary Sara Salvania letter on Richard Rothstein's Apr 26 article holds merit pay for teachers should not be based on test scores</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Arguing Against Merit Pay as Incentive for Teachers'' (Lessons column, April 26):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Arguing Against Merit Pay as Incentive for Teachers'' (Lessons column, April 26):</p>
        <p>Besides all the points that Richard Rothstein noted, a clear reason merit pay for teachers should not be based on test scores was the debacle of discovering last year that some New York City teachers had helped their students cheat on tests. If teachers' pay depended on the achievement of students on tests, wouldn't that be incentive enough for teachers to help their students cheat again? Where does the raising of the quality of education come in?</p>
        <p>MARY  SARA  SALVANIA  Oberlin, Ohio, April 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
